---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
export const prerender = true;

const pageTitle = "Damilare Osibanjo — Personal Wiki";
const pageDescription = "Personal wiki for Damilare Osibanjo — systems programmer, security researcher, and compiler engineer.";
const pageUrl = "https://devdami.varityweb.com/wiki";
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} canonical={pageUrl}>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-content">
    <!-- Wiki header -->
    <div class="border-b border-border/60 pb-3 mb-6">
      <p class="text-[10px] font-mono text-muted/40 tracking-wider mb-1">
        From Damilare's Personal Wiki, the free encyclopedia
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold text-text-dark">
        Damilare Osibanjo
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xs text-muted/60 font-mono mt-1">
        /dəˈmɪlərɛɪ ˌoʊʃɪˈbɑndʒoʊ/
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_280px] gap-8">
      <!-- Main content -->
      <div class="min-w-0">
        <!-- TOC -->
        <div class="border border-border/50 bg-surface/20 rounded-md p-4 mb-6 text-sm">
          <div class="font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono text-xs tracking-wider mb-2">
            Contents
          </div>
          <ul class="space-y-1">
            <li><a href="#biography" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">1. Biography</a></li>
            <li class="ml-4"><a href="#early-life" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">1.1 Early life and education</a></li>
            <li class="ml-4"><a href="#career" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">1.2 Career</a></li>
            <li><a href="#notable-works" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">2. Notable works</a></li>
            <li class="ml-4"><a href="#compilers" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">2.1 Compilers and languages</a></li>
            <li class="ml-4"><a href="#security" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">2.2 Security research</a></li>
            <li class="ml-4"><a href="#tools" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">2.3 Developer tools</a></li>
            <li><a href="#skills" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">3. Technical skills</a></li>
            <li><a href="#philosophy" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">4. Engineering philosophy</a></li>
            <li><a href="#see-also" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">5. See also</a></li>
            <li><a href="#references" class="text-accent hover:underline text-[13px]">6. References</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Biography -->
        <section id="biography" class="mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono border-b border-border/40 pb-1 mb-4">
            <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">1.</span>Biography
          </h2>

          <section id="early-life" class="mb-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono mb-3">
              <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">1.1</span>Early life and education
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed mb-3">
              <strong class="text-text-dark">Damilare Osibanjo</strong> is a Nigerian-born systems and software programmer. 
              He began his programming journey at approximately age 12, initially developing games on the Roblox platform 
              using the Lua scripting language. This early exposure to structured logic and event-driven programming 
              laid the foundation for his later work in systems engineering.<sup class="text-accent text-[10px]">[1]</sup>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed mb-3">
              At age 14, he transitioned to Python, spending approximately three years building automation tools, 
              API integrations, and backend services. During this period, his focus shifted from "how do I build this?" 
              to understanding internal system behavior — memory consumption, concurrency mechanics, and operating 
              system coordination.<sup class="text-accent text-[10px]">[2]</sup>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed mb-3">
              By age 15–16, he was designing backend infrastructure, exploring authentication systems, database 
              architectures, logging patterns, and performance trade-offs. This phase drove him toward lower-level 
              programming in Rust, Go, and C — languages that enforce discipline around memory safety, ownership, 
              and undefined behavior.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">
              At 17, his work sits at the intersection of <strong class="text-text-dark">cybersecurity</strong>, 
              <strong class="text-text-dark">systems programming</strong>, and 
              <strong class="text-text-dark">performance-aware architecture</strong>.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section id="career" class="mb-4">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono mb-3">
              <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">1.2</span>Career
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Damilare is self-taught, with no formal computer science education. His portfolio includes 
              compilers, runtime tools, emulators, programming languages, security research, and distributed 
              infrastructure — all built as independent projects. He maintains an active presence on 
              <a href="https://github.com/dev-dami" class="text-accent hover:underline">GitHub</a> 
              and publishes technical writing on his 
              <a href="/blog" class="text-accent hover:underline">blog</a> covering security vulnerabilities, 
              compiler internals, and systems engineering.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">
              His work has included developing the <strong class="text-text-dark">Carv</strong> programming language 
              (compiling to C for ARM Cortex-M targets), conducting security audits of open-source tools like 
              Langflow (CVE-2026-33017), and building the Xelvo compiler infrastructure.
            </p>
          </section>
        </section>

        <!-- Notable Works -->
        <section id="notable-works" class="mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono border-b border-border/40 pb-1 mb-4">
            <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">2.</span>Notable works
          </h2>

          <section id="compilers" class="mb-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono mb-3">
              <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">2.1</span>Compilers and languages
            </h3>
            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">Carv</strong> — An opinionated programming language that compiles 
                to C for ARM Cortex-M embedded targets. Carv implements Pratt parsing, type inference, ownership 
                tracking, C code generation, and a state-machine-based async/await system. The project is a deep 
                exploration of compiler design for constrained environments.<sup class="text-accent text-[10px]">[3]</sup>
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">Xelvo</strong> — Compiler infrastructure and runtime tools 
                representing his evolving work in language design and compilation. Details are in active development.
              </p>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section id="security" class="mb-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono mb-3">
              <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">2.2</span>Security research
            </h3>
            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">CVE-2026-33017</strong> — Discovered a remote code execution 
                vulnerability in Langflow (a popular open-source LLM application builder). The vulnerability 
                chain involves arbitrary Python code execution through Custom Component nodes, reaching 
                <code class="text-accent text-xs">exec()</code> through eight call-chain layers with zero 
                sandboxing. Published a detailed 
                <a href="/blog/langflow-cve-2026-33017-rce" class="text-accent hover:underline">technical analysis</a> 
                of the exploit chain.<sup class="text-accent text-[10px]">[4]</sup>
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">Attack chain analysis</strong> — Published research on multi-stage 
                exploit chains combining command injection, race conditions, and blind RCE exfiltration, with 
                layered defense strategies. See the full 
                <a href="/blog/attack-chain-command-injection-rce" class="text-accent hover:underline">attack chain analysis</a>.<sup class="text-accent text-[10px]">[5]</sup>
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">XSS methodology</strong> — Developed a comprehensive testing 
                methodology for cross-site scripting vulnerabilities in TanStack Query applications, covering 
                the gap between framework-level XSS protections and real-world data flow exploits.
                Read the 
                <a href="/blog/xss-testing-methodology-tanstack-query" class="text-accent hover:underline">XSS methodology guide</a>.<sup class="text-accent text-[10px]">[6]</sup>
              </p>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section id="tools">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono mb-3">
              <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">2.3</span>Developer tools
            </h3>
            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">Kiattp</strong> — An HTTP testing toolkit for API development 
                and debugging.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">Lexon JS</strong> — A lexical analysis library for JavaScript 
                and TypeScript applications.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">Yems</strong> — A YAML-based email templating system.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-text-dark">Game Boy emulator (Zig)</strong> — A cycle-accurate Game Boy 
                emulator written in Zig. The project explores memory-mapped I/O, interrupt handling, timer 
                synchronization, and audio channel emulation. Includes detailed 
                <a href="/blog/game-boy-emulator-zig-lessons" class="text-accent hover:underline">write-ups</a> 
                on architectural decisions made during development.<sup class="text-accent text-[10px]">[7]</sup>
              </p>
            </div>
          </section>
        </section>

        <!-- Technical Skills -->
        <section id="skills" class="mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono border-b border-border/40 pb-1 mb-4">
            <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">3.</span>Technical skills
          </h2>
          <div class="overflow-x-auto border border-border/50 rounded-md">
            <table class="w-full text-sm min-w-[400px]">
              <thead>
                <tr class="bg-surface/40 border-b border-border/50">
                  <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-left font-medium text-text-dark font-mono text-xs tracking-wider">Category</th>
                  <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-left font-medium text-text-dark font-mono text-xs tracking-wider">Technologies</th>
                  <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-left font-medium text-text-dark font-mono text-xs tracking-wider">Proficiency</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody class="divide-y divide-border/30">
                <tr class="hover:bg-surface/20">
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Systems</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-text">Rust, Go, C</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Advanced</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-surface/20">
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Backend</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-text">TypeScript, Node.js, Python</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Advanced</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-surface/20">
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Web</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-text">React, Astro, Tailwind CSS</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Intermediate</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-surface/20">
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Compiler</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-text">Pratt parsing, codegen, IR design</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Intermediate</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-surface/20">
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Security</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-text">Penetration testing, CVE research, SAST</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Intermediate</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="hover:bg-surface/20">
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Infrastructure</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-text">Docker, Linux, PostgreSQL, Redis</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-xs text-muted font-mono">Intermediate</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Philosophy -->
        <section id="philosophy" class="mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono border-b border-border/40 pb-1 mb-4">
            <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">4.</span>Engineering philosophy
          </h2>
          <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              Damilare advocates for understanding systems at the lowest feasible level of abstraction. 
              He argues that working close to the hardware — compilers, memory models, kernel behavior — 
              fundamentally changes how one designs at the application layer. This philosophy is reflected 
              in his project choices: building a Game Boy emulator to understand memory-mapped I/O, 
              writing a compiler to internalize code generation, and analyzing CVEs to study real-world exploit mechanics.
            </p>
            <p>
              He is critical of "zero-cost abstraction" claims that ignore cognitive costs, and favors 
              explicit, readable code over clever indirection. His blog post on 
              <a href="/blog/zero-language-agent-first-PoC" class="text-accent hover:underline">Zero's agent architecture</a> 
              argues that structured JSON output for compiler errors solves approximately 1% of the actual 
              bottleneck — context management and multi-step planning reliability.
            </p>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-accent/40 pl-4 py-2 my-4 text-sm text-text-muted italic bg-surface/10 rounded-r-md">
              "Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication."
              <br />
              <span class="text-xs text-muted/60 not-italic">— Damilare's personal motto, displayed on his homepage</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- See Also -->
        <section id="see-also" class="mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono border-b border-border/40 pb-1 mb-4">
            <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">5.</span>See also
          </h2>
          <ul class="space-y-1.5 text-sm">
            <li>
              <a href="/about" class="text-accent hover:underline">About page</a>
              <span class="text-muted/50 text-xs ml-2">— Extended biography and timeline</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a href="/projects" class="text-accent hover:underline">Projects</a>
              <span class="text-muted/50 text-xs ml-2">— Complete project portfolio with GitHub stats</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a href="/blog" class="text-accent hover:underline">Blog</a>
              <span class="text-muted/50 text-xs ml-2">— Technical articles and security research</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a href="/uses" class="text-accent hover:underline">/uses</a>
              <span class="text-muted/50 text-xs ml-2">— Development setup and tooling</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a href="/resume" class="text-accent hover:underline">Resume</a>
              <span class="text-muted/50 text-xs ml-2">— Professional summary</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- References -->
        <section id="references" class="mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono border-b border-border/40 pb-1 mb-4">
            <span class="text-accent/60 mr-2">6.</span>References
          </h2>
          <ol class="space-y-1.5 text-xs text-muted leading-relaxed list-decimal list-inside">
            <li class="hover:text-text transition-colors">
              <a href="/about" class="text-accent hover:underline">"About Damilare Osibanjo"</a> — devdami.varityweb.com
            </li>
            <li class="hover:text-text transition-colors">
              <a href="/about" class="text-accent hover:underline">"My Story"</a> — Extended biography on about page
            </li>
            <li class="hover:text-text transition-colors">
              <a href="/blog/carv-opinionated-language" class="text-accent hover:underline">"Carv: An Opinionated Language Compiling to C for ARM Cortex-M"</a> — Technical deep dive
            </li>
            <li class="hover:text-text transition-colors">
              <a href="/blog/langflow-cve-2026-33017-rce" class="text-accent hover:underline">"Langflow CVE-2026-33017: Remote Code Execution Analysis"</a> — Security advisory
            </li>
            <li class="hover:text-text transition-colors">
              <a href="/blog/attack-chain-command-injection-rce" class="text-accent hover:underline">"How Attackers Chain Command Injection, Race Conditions, and Blind RCE"</a> — Attack chain breakdown
            </li>
            <li class="hover:text-text transition-colors">
              <a href="/blog/xss-testing-methodology-tanstack-query" class="text-accent hover:underline">"XSS Testing Methodology for TanStack Query"</a> — Security testing guide
            </li>
            <li class="hover:text-text transition-colors">
              <a href="/blog/game-boy-emulator-zig-lessons" class="text-accent hover:underline">"Building a Game Boy Emulator in Zig: Lessons Learned"</a> — Emulator development postmortem
            </li>
          </ol>
        </section>
      </div>

      <!-- Infobox (Wikipedia-style sidebar) -->
      <aside class="min-w-0">
        <div class="border border-border/50 bg-surface/20 rounded-md overflow-hidden lg:sticky lg:top-24">
          <!-- Infobox header -->
          <div class="bg-accent/10 border-b border-border/50 px-4 py-3 text-center">
            <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-dark font-mono">Damilare Osibanjo</h3>
            <p class="text-[10px] text-muted/60 font-mono mt-0.5">Systems &amp; Software Programmer</p>
          </div>

          <!-- Avatar -->
          <div class="flex justify-center py-4 px-4 border-b border-border/30 bg-surface/20">
